reviewText: 80-76%-perfect75-71%-awsome70-66%-good65-61%-poor6-56%-awful1. Scott 3 hotty and albert vs. test and christian- This was basicly just a filler match. No storyline at all but it got the crowd into it and kept a preaty good pace for the match. I always notice that scotty gets his partners involved which hypes up the crowd. Decent opener. Winners scotty and albert. Match Rating 6/10.2. Edge vs. William Regal for the ITC title- This was an average match. I think that they let this match run a little bit to long. It was good intensity for a while but then most of the match was worked on edges arm. Still decent and was passable for a title match but i know these two could have done alot better. Winner and still ITC champ edge. Match Rating 7/10.3. Jeff Hardy vs. Matt Hardy- I really enjoyed this match. I wish the fued would have lasted a little bit longer after the match but during it played a perfect storyline. It was a fast paced match and the wwe gave these two enough time to work out a good match. SOme good intensity by both men but it was slowed down by working on jeffs leg. A wierd ending to the match but i understand waht the wwe was thinking. Good match. Winner jeff hardy. Match Rating 8/10.4. Big Show and kane vs. the dudleys for the tag team titles- This was an average tag team match. I think that it was a nice idea to put kane and the big show as a team. It was more funny at times in the match but it was still average. I thought that the big show and kane were going to win. Nothing much to sya except it was a soilid tag match. Winners and still wwe tag team champs the dudleys. Match ARting 6.5/10.5. Undertaker vs. Rvd for the hardcore title- This was a really good match. I knew it was a good idea to have these two in a match when they can bring so much to the table. There were not as many hardcore spots as i thought there were going to be but some good stuff. A really nice dive by rvd from the balcony onto taker. Some nice chair shots in this match by rvd and a really nice ending to the match when rvd was chockeslammed off the stage through 2 tables. Winner and new wwe hardcore champ the undertaker. Match Rating 8.5/10.6. Trish vs. Jackilan for the womens title- This was just a match to slow the crowd down after that hardcore match. Both of these divas have alot of talent but i just could not get into this match at all. Maybe just me. Winner and still wwe womens champ trish. Match Rating 5.5/10.7. Stone Cold vs. Kurt angle for the wwe title-  This was not as good as there previous match like the one they had at summerslam but it was still very good. Austin and angle can always bring alot to the table. Not as much of near falls as i was hoping. There was a nice spot were we got to see angles moonsault. Not the decision i was hoping for and i wish the match would have lasted a little bit longer. Still goo. Winner and still wwe champ stone cold steve austin. Match Rating 7.5/10.8. Y2J vs. The Rock for the WCW title- This in my opinion was better than the austin rock match which surprised me. It was just faster paced and was more intense. A really different ending than i was expecting. Some nice spots in this match one of them occuring with a ddt through the announce table. Some more near falls than the other but the ending was kind of weak but it surprised me which is a good thing. Winner and new WCW champ Y2J. Match Rating 9/10.9. Stone Cold vs. Y2J for the undispuited title- This was a nice way to end the ppv. It was started right after the jerico match and started good with a chair shot and a rock bootom. It picked up from there with just some good wrestling and it continued for the rest of the match. proboly could have been a little bit better but it was a good main event and the ending surprised me. Winner and undisputed champ Y2J. Match Rating 8/10.Well that raps up another. I would give vengence 2001 a grade of 66/90 which is a 73% which means this is an awsome ppv. I think that is fair to say. It did not have a bad match on the whole card and we made a little bit of history as weel. If you can tell me if my review was helpful or not. Thanks for your time.
summary: wwe vengence 2001 is a 4 star ppv

reviewText: To sum this all up, this was a flaccid way to end 2001, which had seen one of the best Wrestlemanias in history, and some of the most ground-breaking and ground-failing TV in wrestling history---Stone Cold Steve Austin turning heel, a mass invasion of two other wrestling companies, and the emergence of relatively new superstars like Rob Van Dam and Chris Jericho to superstardom.  And they topped this all off with a "status-quo" humdrum average sort of event.First Vince comes out, and really powerhouses his heel abilities in getting the crowd riled up.  I've always admired Vince's sheer charisma in getting people to hate him; as of late, that's really been weak and uninteresting, and consisting of just doing things that would make the audience mad; but here, he just completely channelled everything that made a good heel, and threw it at the crowd.  Phenomenal.  Ric Flair comes out and says PPV time, and Albert and Scotty 2 Hotty come down the ring to dance with Vince before Vince storms out.Scotty 2 Hotty and Albert vs Test and ChristianFrom the beginning, this is what I expected to be the warm-up for a stellar event.  After watching the event, this turns out to be probably the second best, or probably best match of the night.  Everyone is completely on, putting on great WWF-style wrestling with nonstop action and constant momentum shifts.  Powerful stuff, and if only they pushed these four guys like this more often, they'd all STILL BE IN THE COMPANY.  (9/10)WWF Intercontinental ChampionshipEdge (C) vs William RegalAs boring as any regular TV match with Regal and someone else.  I know Regal is legitimately talented as a chain wrestler, but was it just laziness or the booking getting to him that he came off as dull as Hardcore Holly in this match?  It was lackluster, boring, and the audience didn't care about it.  (0/10)Neat sort of build up to the break-up of the Hardy Boys, but they really make it too blatant that Matt is going to be the heel.Matt Hardy vs Jeff Hardy  Lita special refereeIf these two are dynamite together, they are wet bathwater together.  The match was almost entirely brawling, with a few high spots, but mostly generic Hardcore Holly vs John Cena type brawling.  Lita is so unremarkable as referee that she may as well not be there; her only saving grace was the Dusty finish, paving the way for their eventual breakup.  (3/10)The Rock promises to screw Trish after they win their respective matches.WWF Tag Team ChampionshipThe Dudley Boys (C) vs The Big Show and KaneThe only highlight of this match was The Big Show showing off his powerhouse skill.  Little more than a glorified squash of the Dudley Boys.  I forgot who won, and I only just saw the match yesterday.  (1/10)WWF Hardcore ChampionshipThe Undertaker vs Rob Van Dam (C)The Undertaker is heel here.  But most of the arena cheers him anyway.  The match itself was very dull.  Standard forced "hardcore" affair of trying to be like ECW by having the superstars fight in the crowd.  But they did little more than generic brawling, fake punches, and below-average chair shots.  Even Van Dam's jump off the railings was cut short by the Undertaker's 6'10" height, plus maybe 2-3 foot arms, reaching up to catch him, making for a weak-looking spot.  And god forbid the ECW guy should win out over the WWF original!  (5/10)WWF Women's ChampionshipTrish Stratus vs JacquelineTypical WWF/WWE women's affair... that is, barely anything of worth beyond some sloppy moves and generic brawling.  (0/10)WWF ChampionshipStone Cold Steve Austin (C) vs Kurt AngleBy now, we've seen these two wrestle so much (Summerslam, Unforgiven, No Mercy, Survivor Series) that quite frankly, I'm sick of it.  There was nothing new, nothing special, nothing remarkable about this match.  Austin was mostly restrained in his wrestling, clearly saving up for his next opponent.  The submission holds were weak, sloppy things that looked to be barely there.  (0/10)Test barges into Trish's locker room while she's covered with a towel and basically threatens to rape her, until she shuffles him out and he just leaves despite the door being open.  The hell?  Useless backstage promo FTLNot WCW World ChampionshipThe Rock (C) vs Chris JerichoThis was certainly better than the WWF Championship match, but it wasn't much better.  It was still much of a generic brawl, and Jericho did basically two high flying moves or so in the match.  The submission holds, just like the previous match, were so sloppily applied that there is absolutely no way you could think they would be painful.  Imagine someone basically crouching over your rear end and holding your legs up bent at the knee, while the rest of your body is totally straight.  That's pretty much all it was.  (5.5/10)WWF Undisputed ChampionshipStone Cold Steve Austin vs Chris JerichoImmediately after winning, Jericho has to face Austin.  And everything that Austin held back in his Angle match, perhaps knowing or realizing that it was a boring little affair repeated for the fifth or eighteenth time, unleashed on Jericho.  The absolute best of the WWF on display, with Jericho barely hanging on, yet managing to look tough against Austin.  Austin sells his gimmick so much, he would legitimately frighten me in real life... I couldn't imagine this guy reading a book, reading the newspaper beyond the sports section or the comics, or being able to understand the whole concept of kayfabe.  But he does.  And he sells it to perfection.I would have rated this pay per view as average, 3/5 stars, and this match a full 10/10 if it weren't for the fact that this is supposed to be Jericho's night; he's supposed to have completed his journey from his debut in 1999, from his time in WCW before that, ECW, independent wrestling, all just to make it to the big time, to be at the top of the WWF, the last standing major wrestling promotion in the US!  And they screw him out of this.They screw Jericho out of that glory.  Because during the match, every loser from the previous match and his asshole come and interfere.  First Angle beats up Austin, then The Rock beats up Jericho, then Earl Hebner is knocked out, then Vince McMahon attacks Austin, and sends Nick Patrick out.  Then Ric Flair comes and stops Patrick from counting.  Austin beats up McMahon.  Then Booker T (who should be kayfabe fired) comes and attacks Austin, and Jericho picks up the pin.So according to the WWF, Stone Cold Steve Austin is their unstoppable juggernaut, and Chris Jericho, a former ECW and WCW superstar despite being in the WWF for two years, isn't good enough to make history by himself---he needs three men and a crooked referee to try and defeat Austin.  Pathetic.  (5/10)WWF arrogance at its best, Jericho is nothing more than the random twit who happens to get lucky against the WWF's untouchable superstar who absolutely cannot lose too many matches cleanly, Stone Cold Steve Austin.  I love Austin as a wrestler, I think he's one of the best in the business.  I know he has legitimate technical prowess despite the WWF making him a brawler.  But for god's sake... the WWF, taking a page out of WCW's book (just like today) just can't let go of their tried and true top guys for a little while and let a new rising star reach the top.  So what if Jericho is a heel?  That doesn't mean heels are inferior superstars, or that he doesn't deserve to cleanly beat the best guy in the company for its top prize.  Horrible.
summary: Couldn't even give Jericho a clean victory for his first ever world championship

reviewText: This Historic event will decide the 1st ever undisputed champion which was live from San Dieago, C.A.-Vince speaks to crowd (A$$ Kisser)-Flair interupts Vince.WOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOO-Scotty and Albert vs Test and ChristianNice opener that got the crowed worked up.It was a decent fast and short tag team match which was entertaining.-Regal interview-Edge vs Regal (Intercontinental Championship)The macth is nothing special and displays more of regals style of wrestling which is slow and offensive.Not much difference to there RAW matches but tonight the brass knucks didnt help Regal.-Ric Flair and Angle promo-Lita and Matt promo-Hardy vs Hardy rivalry-Matt Hardy vs Jeff HardySpecial guest referee : LitaBrother vs brother was not what we'd all expected from these highflyers.This is the match where the Hardy Boyz were suspended for about a month as they were suppose to display a highflying affair but instead the Hardyz ignored the writers and tried to put on a technical match that they couldnt do well.It was good having Lita as the special guest referee as it made the match more interesting.A little dissapointing from a much anticapated match.-Rock and Trish promo-Dudley Boyz vs Bigshow and Kane (WWF tag team championships on the line)The match was nothing special, it had a few power spots but not as much as you would expect.This match was fit for RAW or Smackdown.-Lita and Matt promo-Rivalry of Rob Van Dam and Undertaker-RVD vs Undertaker (Hardcore championship)RVD  starts off with some of his unorfadox offense style but Undertaker is quick to put a stop to it.This match is different compared to RVD's other past Hardcore bouts as this one is more of a brawl not much wrestling in the ring at all.They mainly fought on the entrance way.Nice cross body off the balcony.The match was good, not the best, but good and ends with RVD getting chokeslammed off the entrance way through tables.Also i would like to add something, if you have enjoyed RVD's hardcore matches latley against Jeff Hardy and Jericho, i suggest you have a look at some ECW dvd's because you aint seen nothing yet.-Ric Flair and Jericho Promo-Trish vs Jackie (Womens title)The match was pretty good and started to impress me, but i wish it went for longer as the crowd started getting into it.-Replay from Smackdown where Vince kissed a whole lotta A$$-Rikishi interview at WWF New York-The build up to the tournament for the Undisputed Championship4 MEN / 3 MATCHES / 2 TITLES / 1 UNDISPUTED CHAMPIONJERICHO  /  ROCK  /  ANGLE  /  STONE COLD STEVE AUSTIN-WWF CHAMPIONSHIPKurt Angle vs Stone Cold Steve AustinStarts off with some grappling then into some Austin brawling.It is a hard fought match with a lot of german suplexes  and Austin ends up going to the finals for the Undisputed Championship-Trish and Test Promo-WORLD CHAMPIONSHIPRock vs JerichoThe match starts off a bit slow but does pick up, with Jericho's cockyness and Rocks charisma makes it interesting but not there best display as they have had way better matches (No Mercy 2001). Nice table spot though and a couple of cose pins until Vince comes out and Jericho makes a date with Austin for the Undisputed Championship.-WINNER IS THE 1ST EVER UNDISPUTED CHAMPION OF THE WORLDStone Cold Steve Austin vs Chris JerichoThe match starts with both guys nearly getting counted out as Angle hit Austin with a chair and Rock rockbottoms Jericho.Austin gets up and starts off his usual offense of smash mouth in your face style in and out of the ring.By now you have to give Jericho credit as hasnt had a break or a breather after his bout with the Rock.This match is a slobber Knocker until Booker-t makes his return  and Jericho gets the push of his career by becoming the 1st ever Undisputed Champion.The event itself could have been a bit better but no doubt it was historical.My favourite match being the Hardcore Title and the most dissapionting match was the Hardy Boyz match as we all know could have been a classic.If you are a true Jerichoholic you should already have this in your collection, if you are a WWF collecter this is a must for your collection because of the crowning of the 1st Undisputed Champion.If you are browsing around looking for a wrestling vhs/dvd i would recomend you to look around a bit more as it isnt too rewatchable to the new fan.

reviewText: Solid PPV, and one of the best I've ever seen...To start things off, Vince comes out and starts whining and complaining about have his face shoved into Rikishi's ... He says who laughs last, laughs loudest...! The Ric Flair comes out and stops Vince's incessive whining so we can get on with our PPV.Match #1 Test & Christian vs. Scotty 2 Hotty & Albert: What a crappy way to start this awesome PPV. Scotty and Albert win in this waste of a match. I'm glad Stray-Train was fired! Scotty needs to go next! DUD!!! 3/10Regal is seen spouting off some nonsense about how he will beat Edge, and how he has the power of the punch or something (can we say "brass knucks"???) Then he calls Coach a PILLOCK and heads out to the ring.Match #2 Edge (c) vs. William Regal for the Intercontinental Championship: A decent match, but nothing spectacular. Regal and Edge's styles don't work well together. Edge retains after the Edgeucution! 6/10Ric is bakestage talking on his phone and Kurt walks in and basically just spouts a bunch of stuff about him being a gold medalist and that he will be the UDC! Flair wishes him luck and he leaves.Quick meeting between Lita and Matt Hardy before the match...Match #3 Matt vs. Jeff with Lita as the Special Guest Referee: Great match, and this is where things started to pick up! Lita counts the 1,2,3 and Jeff wins but Matt's foot was on the rope! Matt gets pissed and leaves! 8/10Rock and Trish meet up backstage and she gives him a kiss. Then Rock says after he becomes the UDC, Trish will have plenty of time to Smell What the Rock is Cookin'...(HOOKUP!)Match #4 The Dudleys vs. Kane and The Big Show for the Tag Team Championships: Decent match with Kane and Big Show getting pissed at eachother the whole time. This lead to their downfall and the Dudleys retain! 7/10Lita apologizes to Matt for not seeing his foot on the rope. Matt acts like a cry baby and walks off.Match #5 RVD (c) vs. The Undertaker for the Hardcore Championship: I know everyone wants to give me hell for hating the Undertaker, but now he is just a fat old man who is getting his horrible push cuz of his political power much like HHH. Anyways he beats RVD in a brutal match, but the only problem is there is no blood what so ever!!! 8/10 for good crowd interaction in this match!Ric is back talking on his cell when Jericho comes in. He also spouts stuff about him beating Rock twice and that no one thinks he will be UDC. He tells Flair he will win and then he leaves. (Why do the heels whine so much?)Match #6 Trish (c) vs. Jackie for the Women's Championship: DUD!!! Trish retains cuz Jackie sucks and I'm glad she was fired! 0/10WWF New York with a quick interview with Rikishi. Then they show the higlights of Vince's escapade with the Rock and Rikishi on Smackdown. Very funny segment and I'm glad it was on the PPV because this DVD has absolutely no extras!!!Match #7 Stone Cold (c) vs. Kurt Angle for the WWF Championship: Great way to start off this little tournament. After lots of suplexes, Stone Cold wins with a STUNNER! He retains and moves on to the main event match for the UDC. 9/10That perv Test breaks into Trish's dressing room and offers to give her a congratulations kiss. She calls him crazy, and in the midst of his whining, she kicks him out.Match #8 Chris Jericho vs. The Rock for the World Heavyweight Championship: AWESOME! Great action in this match. Vince makes and interferrence to distract Rock and the ref. Jericho nails a low blow and a rock bottom on Rock and wins! 10/10Match #9 Jericho vs. Stone Cold for the UDC: Definitely the match of the card but since both these guys had already wrestled, it was over around the 10 minute mark. I think there was an interferrence by just about everyone here...first Kurt, then Rock, then Vince, then Ric Flair!!! Total CHAOS!!! Looked like Austin was gonna pull it off when Booker T snuck up behind and clocked Austin in the back of the head with the WWF Title!!! When Booker came out this is when the crowd got the loudest, even louder then Flair! Jericho got the 1,2,3 and became the first ever Undisputed Champion!!! Vince laughs last and laughs loudest after all!!! 10000000/10!!!I know I write too much, but had to get the most out of this PPV!!! Go get this if you can still find it!!!

reviewText: WWF VENGEANCE 12.09.01 SAN DIEGO, CAWell this was a very anticipated ppv on my part.  The event took place at the Sports Arena.  I had my picture made there in 6.2004.  Oh well anyway lets get to a packed show.Opening Match1. Scotty 2 Hotty and Albert vs Test and ChristianAn alright match with Albert getting the pin on Christian.4/102. Intercontinental Championship MatchEdge (c) vs William RegalI thought that Regal was going to win but Edge comes out of  nowhere with a Spear that allows him to get the pin.5/103. WWF Tag Team Championship MatchThe Dudley Boys (c)s vs Big Show and Kaneno technical ability in this one.  Im not saying anyone of them is a bad athelete but none of them are known like Chris Benoits.ends with Bubba Pinning The Big Show.4/104. Matt Hardy vs Jeff Hardy (Lita as Special Guest Referee)Good Match as both pretty much Knew each other.  Jeff gets the pin but Lita didnt see Matts foot on the rope.6/105. WWF Hardcore Championship MatchRob Van Dam (c) vs The UndertakerOne of the best hardcore title matches I ever saw.  Lots of action around the ring with 'Taker giving RVD a Chokeslam off the entrance ramp onto a table for the 1-2-3.6.5/106. WWF Womens Championship MatchTrish Stratus (c) vs JacqulineEnds with Trish getting a Backslide on Jacquline for the pin.2/107. WWF Championship MatchStone Cold Steve Austin (c) vs Kurt AngleAwesome match between the two with both men taking it hard to one another and Austin getting the win after a Stunner.7/108. WCW Championship MatchThe Rock (c) vs Chris JerichoBest match of the night.  Jericho was the only one of the four men who had never won the WWF Title.  I had Jericho as my pick to win it all.  Ends with Jericho pinning The Rock after hitting a ...Rock Bottom!  To win the WCW Title.8/109. WWF and WCW Championships Unification MatchStone Cold Steve Austin (WWF c) vs Chris Jericho (WCW c)Jericho doesnt even get a break as Austin comes straight out after him.  Just a brawl with all kinds of stuff.  Jericho wins after Ric Flair,Vince McMahon,The Rock,Kurt Angle and Booker T who clocks Austin with the WWF belt interfere.  Jericho pins Austin after the belt shot to get the 3 count and become the first ever Undisputed WWF Champion!!!!  Jericho was my pick and he beat both The Rock and Stone Cold Steve Austin in the same night to become Champion.7.5/10

reviewText: WWF Vengance bombed big time. I'm sayin' take the biggest f*ckin' bomb known to man and multiply it's explosion by 500. (warning, much sarcasm ahead)I mean what more could you want than an exciting, ground-breaking encounter teaming Test (cough) and Christian (double cough) vs. Albert (choke) with Scotty 2 Hotty (croak). What an amazing bout this will be. Oh boy, this is the match I have looked forward for ages and finally it's here! To tell you the truth, this match sucked worse than an Afghani porn-star!Albert uses his Baldo Bomb for the win(I doubt it will matter though) at 6:12  Rating-DudEdge (minor clap) vs. William (I want pain-killers) Regal:This match was very dissapointing for many reasons. They both have the abilty to go at it for 20 minutes without leaving the ring or doing any cheap-shots. This match however had the much used "Brass Knucks" finish backfire on Regal. I mean, Brass Knucks are not even Legal in the U.S. so that just ruins what little reality there is left in Wrestling. Edge spears Regal with Knucks at 9:17 (Come on WWF, I hate to see these two not giving it their all) Rating-1/2*Jeff (Moron, you're going to kill yourself) Hardy vs.Matt (I'm too affraid to jump of the tope rope) Hardy: The Hardyz put on a garbage performance that gets their a$$es suspended for a month beacuse Management told them to do a high flying match but they tried to put on a technical match which they obviously can't handle. It bores the hell out of me to watch this match so I won't even say a think about any of the moves. Jeff Hardy wins at 12:30 Rating-*1/2Dudley (ECW!,ECW!!) Boyz vs Kane (underused) and Big Slow, I mean Show, no no, it's Slow. This is for the Tag Titles and you didn't think that Kane and Big Slow would win, did you? If you did think they were going to win than you got issues. Big Show is way beyond bad that it's freakin' impossible to have a good match with the guy. Dudleyz retain after a double flapjack into the corner with Big Slow at 6:45 Rating-DudRob Van Dam vs Undertaker with a Pee-Wee Herman haircut: This was a pretty good match with the whole f'n show RVD and Deadman Ltd. or whatever they call it. RVD does some cool spots but not enough to save the PPV from it's downward spiral. RVD's Plancha from the top of the Archway was nice looking.Undertaker wins after a Chokeslam off the ramp at 11:05Rating-***Trish Stratus vs. Jackie: Only part I liked was when they worked stiff on each other after a screw-up. Trish wins at 3:35. Rating-*Steve Austin vs. Kurt Angle (WWF Championship): Good match, it's what! what! what! what! what! you would expect from these two considering their feud over the past five or six months. This is the end of the road with the title up for grabs in this four man tournement. Kurt does the ringpost Figure Four! Austin hits his Stunner for the Win at 15:02  Rating-***The Rock vs. Chris Jericho (WCW Championship): This was my favorite match of the night considering Y2J is my favorite wrestler and The Rock is my least favorite wrestler but he can still entertain and maybe pull off some good spots. This match was just as good as their No Mercy incounter. The Rock gives Y2J a nasty looking DDT through the Spanish announce table! Jericho manages to win by giving Rocky the Rock Bottom for the win at 19:06 Rating-***1/2Steve Austin vs. Chris Jericho (Undisputed Championship): Here it is. You figure they would put on a thirty minute technical bout because this match will be entered in the history books move by move. It can't be bad. It has to be good is what I told myself before I sat down to watch the match on PPV. I was dead wrong. It was the worst title bout I have ever seen in my life. It was worse than the Savage-DiBaise WM4 title bout. It was complete, utter, garbage! This match is full of run-ins, ref bumps and the all too foolish chops. The only good move in the match was Austin's Boston Crab. Booker T interferes and hits Austin. Y2J covers him for the win at 12:39 Rating-DudWell, overall this PPV is a spit in the face to every Wrestler in the world who works his A$$ off in god knows where. It's a punch in the face to any title match that was a five-star bout. The Main event of this PPV beats out Taker and Kane vs. Kronic at Unforgiven as the worst match ever!Johnny America
summary: Vengance fails to live up to it's Hype!

reviewText: This was actually a pretty decent PPV.  It is an overall underrated PPV, which is surprising considering the first ever undisputed title is handed out in this match.1. Scotty 2 Hotty & Albert vs. Test & ChristianThese were the early days of Test and Christian teaming together.  Nothing to exciting here.  Why is Albert still employed, and Scotty for that matter.  (7/10)2. Edge vs. William Regal (Intercontinental Title)This was the beginning of these two competitors fued.  Unfortunately, the fued did not live up to the hype and really dragged on.  Okay match.  (7/10)3. Jeff Hardy vs. Matt HardyThis fued did not last long and good thing it didn't. I was really looking forward to this match.  It was a complete dud.  (4/10)4. Dudley Boys vs. Big Show & Kane (WWF Tag Titles)Nothing too much went on in this match.  It was more funny than anything.  (6/10)5. Rob Van Dam vs. Undertaker (Hardcore Title)One of the better matches of the night.  These two actually mixed well together in this match and put on quite a performance.  (8.5/10)6. Trish Stratus vs. Jacqueline (WWF Women's Title)Who cares?  (3/10)7. Stone Cold Steve Austin vs. Kurt Angle (Winner Gets A Shot At Undisputed Title Later In The Night)Very entertaining match.  Probably the best match of the night.  These two mix very well together.  Although Angle can hang with anybody and make everyone look good.  (9/10)8. The Rock vs. Chris Jericho (Winner Gets A Shot At Undisputed Title Later In The Night)Decent match.  It is not as good as their No Mercy 2001 and Royal Rumble 2002 title matches, but is good nonetheless.  These two mesh well together as well.  (8.5/10)9. Austin/Angle winner vs. Rock/Jericho winner (To Become The First Ever Undisputed Champion)I don't want to give away the semi-final winners just in case you have not seen the PPV.  Pretty good final match.  Booker T makes an appearance.  Surprise ending.  (9/10)The main event matches on this PPV were good, but the undercard was horrible.  The only real need to buy this DVD is for historical purposes.  The matches were decent, but can be seen elsewhere on other PPV's.Overall Rating:  7/10
summary: December 2001  San Diego Sports Arena  San Diego, CA

reviewText: WWE Vengeance was a great DVD. It was filled was great action. All, yes I mean all the matches were heart pounding. You could never guess what would happen next. The main events were great. There were 4 superstars, 3 main events, 2 titles on the line, and for the first time ever ONE Undisputed Champion. This movie is worth owning. Trust me because I've already seen this movie 5 times and I was there (in person)to see WWE Vengeance.

reviewText: Vengeance review:THIS REVIEW IS VERY LONG AND DOES NOT SHOW IT ALL SO GO TO "SEE ALL MY REVIEWS" AND SEARCH FOR IT THERE TO SEE THE FULL REVIEW !!!1.Test and Christian vs Scotty 2 Hotty and AlbertScotty and Albert attacked Test and Christian before the latter even had a chance to make it to the ring. Scotty dominated in the early-going, and was soon face to face with Test -- only to tag out to Albert! The former T&A; partners went back and forth in a show of size and strength. Scotty & Albert double-teamed Test, until Christian hung Scotty up on the top rope. Test and Christian isolated the innovator of the Worm, assaulting him and preventing him from tagging in Albert. But Scotty fought his way back, and finally got the tag to Albert! The Hip Hop Hippo was a house afire, taking on both of his opponents with reckless abandon. He set Christian up for the Baldobomb, but Test grabbed Albert's legs and pulled him out of the ring. Scotty then bulldogged Christian and was going for the Worm, but Christian caught him and knocked him down. Then Christian went for the Worm! But Albert caught him and was setting him up for a big slam, only to get the big boot from Test for a near fall! Scotty bulldogged Test and then nailed the Worm! Christian went for the Unprettier on Scotty, but Albert nailed the Baldobomb on Christian and pinned him for the win!Winners: Scotty 2 Hotty and Albert2.Intercontinental ChampionshipEdge vs William RegalEdge got the early advantage in the bout, using his speed and agility to his advantage. But Regal lured him outside the ring and knocked him against the ring and the barricade. Back in the ring, Regal nailed Edge with a series of uppercuts, and reversed a sunset flip into a brutal kneedrop. Edge scored a near-fall with an inside cradle, but Regal continued to maintain the advantage. And the crowd continued to stay all over Regal, blasting him with boos and chants of "Regal sucks!" Edge soon took Regal down and scored a few near-falls of his own. He positioned Regal up top and delivered a stunning hurricanrana from the top rope for a two-count! A Northern Lights Suplex scored another two for Edge, and Regal soon took him down with another forearm, before Edge kicked Regal to the outside. Edge went for a spear from the ring apron to the floor, but Regal moved, and Edge speared the steel steps! Regal was now firmly in control, and with the referee distracted, he reached under the ring and pulled out a pair of brass knuckles, stuffing them into his tights! Back in the ring, Regal went for the pin, but Edge got his feet on the ropes. Regal powerbombed Edge for another near fall. A frustrated Regal kept up his assault, but Edge hit an Ghetto Blaster and both men were down. Edge scored a series of near-falls, but Regal wouldn't stay down. Regal taunted the champion, and hit two double-arm underhook suplexes, but Edge kicked out of the pin! Then Edge speared Regal and pinned him to retain his championship!Winner and still champion: Edge3.Jeff Hardy vs Matt HardyLita was the special guest referee.As emotional as this battle of brothers was set to be, it was made all-the-more intense by Lita's role as guest referee. Jeff looked a bit hesitant at first, as did Lita. But Matt looked confident and focused. The two men traded several reversals and lock-ups in the early going, with Matt mocking his brother. Matt took control in the early-going, but Jeff battled his way back. Jeff moved out of the way of Matt's second-rope legdrop, and then hit a falling headbutt and a clothesline on his brother. Jeff then mocked his brother, hitting a second-rope legdrop of his own! Lita counted the two-count on that one. Jeff went up top, but Matt tripped his brother and tied him to the Tree of Woe. Lita then made Matt back up as she untied Jeff and let him get out of the corner! Matt scored a roll-up for two, and went for a sunset flip to the outside which was countered by Jeff, leaving both men lying outside the ring! Back in the ring moments later, Jeff looked to have hurt his left knee, and Lita checked on him. Matt went right to work on Jeff's injured knee, assaulting his brother with a chop block and a series of moves. Matt went for a powerbomb, but Jeff reversed it into a Russian leg sweep, which earned him a two-count. Matt went right back to work, assaulting Jeff with a half Boston crab. Lita screamed at Matt to break the hold once Jeff made it to the ropes. Matt wrenched Jeff's leg again, and went for a spinning toe hold, but Jeff kicked Matt to the outside. Jeff then ran across the ring and kicked Matt right in the face with a baseball slide! Jeff went to leap over the top, but his knee was hurting so bad that he collapsed. Matt grabbed the leg, but Jeff kicked Matt with a mule kick! The brothers slugged it out, and Matt went for the Twist of Fate. But Jeff countered into a legdrop. Jeff suplexed Matt and went up top for the Swanton. But his knee was hurting so much that Matt caught him up top and crotched him on the top rope. Matt tossed his brother from the top and went for the Twist of Fate, but Jeff reversed and went for one of his own! Matt went for a backslide, but Jeff kicked out. Matt went for a pin, but held onto the ropes for leverage, and Lita made him break it up! Jeff tried for a roll-up, but Matt kicked out. Matt continued the attack on his brother, but Jeff was soon up top again. But again Matt caught his brother, and went for the Twist of Fate from the top! But Jeff shoved Matt down and hit a stunning Swanton Bomb! Matt tried to get his foot on the ropes, but Jeff pulled it off, and Lita counted the pinfall, giving Jeff the win! Matt screamed at his girlfriend after the bout!Winner: Jeff Hardy4.Tag Team ChampionshipDudley Boyz vs Big Show and KaneStacy Keibler accompanied the Dudleys to ringside for this title defence against two giants! Kane dominated the Dudleys in the early-going, and then tagged in Big Show, who was just as dominant. Show was set to go for the chokeslam, but Bubba held onto the ropes, raked Show's eyes, and tagged in D-Von. Show hit a sidewalk slam on D-Von for a near fall. Show nailed D-Von with a series of butt-butts (sort of like a headbutt, but with Show using his posterior), and the Show and Kane continued their sheer domination in the ring, knocking the Dudleys from pillar to post. The 500-pound Show soon squashed both Dudleys in the corner! Bubba and D-Von then fell to the outside. Kane went up top and flew to the outside, knocking down both Dudleys! Back in the ring, Stacy tried to rally the troops, but Show snuck up and pulled down her skirt, spanking the Duchess of Dudleyville! The Dudleys hit Kane with a double-suplex, and went to work at isolating the Big Red Machine. They hit the "wassap!" headbutt and a series of double-team manoeuvres. They then set Kane up for the 3-D, but Kane kicked D-Von in the head and clotheslined Bubba. Kane then tagged in Show, who cleaned house! He went for the chokeslam on D-Von, but Bubba nailed him with a chop block. Kane went for a top-rope clothesline on D-Von, but accidentally hit the Show. Bubba went for the cover, but Kane broke it up. The Dudleys fell to the outside, and Show asked why Kane had hit him and moments later, Show accidentally hit Kane! Bubba Ray took the turnbuckle pad off one of the corners, and the Dudleys launched Show into the air, where Show's head hit the exposed turnbuckle! He was then pinned as the Dudleys retained their titles!Winners and still Champions: Dudley Boyz5.Hardcore ChampionshipRob Van Dam vs The UndertakerThe Undertaker rode his motorcycle to the ring, where he would face Rob Van Dam for the Hardcore Championship. Shortly into the bout, RVD scored a near-fall on a top-rope somersault. Taker soon crotched RVD on the top rope and knocked him to the outside. On the outside, Taker went to drive RVD into the ringpost, but RVD reversed and knocked Taker into the post. RVD brutalized Taker with kicks, and knocked him over the barricade and into the people -- perfectly legal in the hardcore environment. He went for a bodypress, but Taker hit him with a punch and RVD was down. The fight made its way through the people, and both men seemed to relish the no-DQ stipulation. Van Dam hit a springboard moonsault for a two-count. Taker soon tossed RVD over a railing onto a concrete floor, and then used it to choke the Hardcore Champion. The fight soon moved into a technical area, where Taker grabbed a steel chair from a stagehand. But when he went to hit RVD, Van Dam hit Taker with a fire extinguisher, following up with a series of kicks. RVD grabbed a trash can and hit Taker over the head. Van Dam climbed up to the cheap seats, and hit a huge cross body from 20 feet in the air for a two-count! RVD continued to lay into the Taker, as the two fought up the staging. RVD scored a near-fall right behind the TitanTron, and out on the stage, RVD hit Taker with a trash-can lid, and then nailed a spinning legdrop. Taker then took advantage, driving Van Dam's head into the staging with a sickening thud! The Undertaker then went for the Last Ride on the stage, but Van Dam held onto the stage and kicked Taker away! With Van Dam down on the stage, Taker went backstage and came back with a chair, which RVD kicked away. RVD gave Taker rolling thunder right on the stage for a two-count! RVD grabbed the chair and dropkicked it right into Taker's face, again for a two-count. RVD went for the Van Daminator but missed, and Taker connected with a brutal chair shot. After a series of reversals on the stage, Taker chokeslammed RVD off the stage and through a number of tables! Three seconds later, Taker was the Hardcore Champion!Winner and new champion: The Undertaker6.Women's ChampionshipTrish Stratus vs JacquelineThe Women's Title was on the line as Trish defended against the rough-and-tumble Jackie, herself a former Women's Champion. Jackie took the advantage in the early-going, knocking Trish to the mat on numerous occasions. But Trish wouldn't stay down. Trish took the advantage with a couple of kicks, but Jackie just shoved her away, and knocked her down with punches and kicks. Jackie slammed Trish down twice, and stepped on the champion's hair. But Trish rebounded with a clothesline for two. Jackie knocked Trish down, but Trish sent Jackie into the corner, and Trish went with a backwards roll for a near-fall. Trish went for the bulldog off the ropes, but Jackie shoved her off, and kicked her in the head for a two-count. Trish then hit a backslide and pinned Jackie to retain her title! The two shook hands after the bout.Winner and still champion: Trish Stratus7.WWF Heavyweight ChampionshipSteve Austin vs Kurt AngleThe first of the three matches to determine an Undisputed Champion pitted Stone Cold Steve Austin against Kurt Angle for the World Wrestling Federation Championship! The two superstars stared each other down as the crowd cheered of anticipation of the first title unification in the history of professional wrestling. With so much on the line, you could cut the intensity with a knife. The two exchanged several lock-ups in the early-going, with both men making clean breaks. As the "Angle sucks" chants began, Austin gained control and pounded on the gold medallist. Angle soon went to the outside to regroup for a few moments. Back in the ring, Angle took Austin down with a go-behind, but Austin escaped and went to the outside to regroup for himself. Back in the ring, Austin gave Angle the middle finger! The two struggled for position, and Angle went for the ankle lock early. But Austin kicked his way out of it. Austin grabbed Angle's arm and went to work on it, before hitting the Olympic hero in the eye. The Rattlesnake choked Angle on the ropes, and continued his assault on Angle's bicep. The Rattlesnake soon launched Angle over the top rope to the outside, and Austin went right out after him, tossing him into the ringpost three times, clearly attacking the left side of Angle's torso! The Rattlesnake also tossed Angle's head off the ring steps for good measure. Back in the ring, Austin used an arm bar takedown on Angle's injured left shoulder to score a near-fall. He slapped away on Angle, but Angle soon rolled through a move and locked in the ankle lock! Austin struggled his way to the ropes, but Angle pulled him right to the center of the ring! But eventually, Austin made it to the ropes, and the ref broke up the hold! Austin launched Angle over the top rope to the outside, and Austin knocked Angle's head into the Spanish announce table, before throwing him back into the ring. But Angle rolled to the outside to get some distance, luring Austin to the ringpost, where he knocked him down and wrapped his leg around the ringpost. Angle slapped away at Stone Cold, and then applied the figure-four leglock on Austin around the ringpost! Back in the ring, Angle again locked on the ankle lock. But Austin rolled through and kicked Angle away. Angle nailed Austin with a belly-to-belly suplex, but Austin pulled himself up. The men slugged it out, and Angle nailed Austin with three successive German suplexes for a two-count. With Austin down, Angle went up top and went for the moonsault -- but Austin moved! Austin continued to pound on Angle, and hit the Olympian with the Lou Thesz Press and a spinebuster, again scoring a two-count. Angle raked Austin's eyes to gain the advantage, but Austin reversed and nailed five successive German suplexes of his own! Still, the Rattlesnake scored just a two-count. As the two skirmished in the ropes, Angle nailed a low blow. He then nailed the Angle slam, but Austin kicked out of the pinfall attempt! Angle was beside himself! Angle went for the Stone Cold Stunner, but Austin reversed into a Stunner of his own! Austin then pinned Angle for a successful title defence!Winner and still Champion: Stone Cold Steve Austin8.World Heavyweight ChampionshipThe Rock vs Chris JerichoThese two bitter rivals met one-on-one for The Rock's World Championship, with the winner going on to meet Stone Cold Steve Austin to crown the first-ever Undisputed Champion! The two exchanged holds and reversals in the early-going, and Rock seemed to be a man on a mission. Y2J soon nailed Rock with a spinning heel kick. He followed up with a top-rope dropkick, knocking Rock to the outside. Y2J drilled Rock's head into the Spanish announcer's table, but Rock battled back and knocked Y2J's head into that same piece of furniture. Jericho drove Rock's head into the steps, and then tossed Rock back into the ring, following up with a top-rope reverse elbow for two. Y2J suplexed the People's Champion, and posed over The Rock, mocking his opponent. He choked Rock on the middle rope. Rocky scored with a flying clothesline, but Jericho kicked out of a pin attempt. As the crowd chanted "Rocky," Y2J went to work on the World Champion, scoring with several near falls. But Rock soon scored with a throw, and a Samoan drop for two. Y2J locked Rock in a sleeper, and the People's Champion looked like he was nearly unconscious. But the World Champion battled back, and soon got to his feet. But Y2J took The Rock back down and went for the Lionsault. Rock moved, but Jericho landed on his feet. The two slugged it out, but Y2J hit the bulldog and nailed the Lionsault! But Rock kicked out at two! Y2J yelled at referee Earl Hebner, even shoving the ref -- and Earl shoved right back! Y2J suplexed Rock, and went up top. But Rock hit the ropes, crutching Jericho up top. Rock smacked Jericho across the chest three times, and went for a superplex, but Y2J threw Rock from the rope and nailed him with a flying bodypress. But Rock rolled through and got a near-fall! Y2J continued his attack on Rock, but Rock moved as Y2J came into the corner, and Jericho fell all the way to the outside! On the outside, Y2J dropped Rock onto the barricade, and slingshotted him into the ringpost. Y2J then took the top off the American announce table, and he and Rock ascended that piece of furniture. He then went to give Rock a Rock Bottom through the table, but Rock reversed it into a DDT right through the table! The referee let the match continue, knowing what was on the line. Rock threw Y2J back into the ring, and set him up for the Rock Bottom. But Y2J battled out of it, and nailed Rock with the Breakdown. Y2J struggled back to his feet and lunged on top of Rock. He then set up Rock for the People's Elbow! But as he went for the move, Rock caught his leg and locked him in the sharpshooter! But Rock reversed the move into a sharpshooter of his own! Rock screamed in pain as Y2J cinched it in in the middle of the ring! Rock seemed to be fading, but made one last lunge for the ropes -- and made it! The ref broke up the hold, but Y2J went for the Walls of Jericho! But Rock rolled him up, and got a two-count! Rock then nailed the Rock Bottom, but was too out of it to make the cover! Down to the ring ran Mr. McMahon, and he distracted Hebner as Rock pinned Jericho. Rock then punched out Vince, and hit Y2J with a spinebuster! Rock went for the People's Elbow, but Vince got in his way, and Rock brought Vince into the ring! He hit the People's Elbow on Jericho and laid the smack down on Vince, and as the ref tended to Vince, Y2J hit a low blow on Rock. Y2J then hit the Rock Bottom on Rock and pinned him to become the World Champion!Winner and still champion: Chris Jericho9.Undisputed World Heavyweight Champion(WWF Heavyweight Champion) Steve Austin vs. (World Champion) Chris JerichoY2J had absolutely NO time to rest, as Stone Cold headed to the ring immediately after Jericho had pinned The Rock! Before the match officially began, Kurt Angle headed to the ring and nailed Austin with a steel chair. Rock responded by giving Jericho a Rock Bottom, and then chasing after Angle! The bell rang, and the first-ever bout for the Undisputed World Championship was underway! Y2J went for a quick pinfall on Austin, but the Rattlesnake kicked out at two. Jericho assaulted Austin, hoping to keep the momentum on his side. Austin soon speared Jericho out of the corner, with a flurry of offence. He drilled Jericho's head into the top turnbuckle repeatedly and went for the Stunner, but Jericho backed out. Austin then knocked Jericho to the outside. Austin brutalized Y2J on the outside, pounding on the World Champion. He repeatedly dropped Jericho onto the barricade and the ringpost. Austin even tore away the mats on the outside, exposing the concrete floor. Jericho clotheslined Austin onto the concrete as Y2J cleared the stuff off the Spanish announce table. He took Stone Cold on top of the table, where Austin went for the Stunner. But Y2J instead went for the Walls of Jericho, trying to turn Austin over. Instead, Austin flipped Jericho off the table and onto the concrete! Austin then suplexed Y2J onto the concrete and tossed him back into the ring. In the ring, Jericho threw Austin shoulder-first into the ringpost twice, and then chopped away at him. Y2J missed a dropkick, and Austin caught him and slingshotted him into the top turnbuckle. Y2J then wrenched Jericho's arm into an armbar, even putting his feet on the ropes to increase his leverage. The ref soon saw Y2J's feet on the ropes and made him break the hold. Y2J continued his assault by suplexing Austin, and Jericho then went up top. But Austin caught him from the top, burying a right hand into Y2J's gut. Austin was now in control, but Y2J ran through a hold and went for the Walls of Jericho. Y2J locked it in in the center of the ring! The Rattlesnake screamed in pain, and finally made it to the ropes, as the ref broke the hold. Y2J stomped at Stone Cold, but soon went for a flying forearm and instead ran into the ref, knocking him to the outside. With no ref, the fight continued on the inside. In the ring, Y2J hit a low blow, and then hit Austin with the Stone Cold Stunner! Mr. McMahon headed to the ring, calling for Nick Patrick, who was wearing a WWF referee's shirt! But Ric Flair came down and pulled Patrick out of the ring, slugging him to the ground! But Vince then sucked-punched Flair, knocking Ric into the ringpost! In the ring, Austin hit a low blow, and then went to the outside and assaulted Mr. McMahon! Back in the ring, Austin hit a Thesz Press, and fists and fire. Austin caught Y2J off the ropes and locked Y2J in the Walls of Jericho -- and Jericho tapped out, but there was no ref to see it! Suddenly, Booker T ran into the ring and nailed Austin in the back of the head with a title belt! Vince McMahon threw Earl Hebner back into the ring, and Y2J covered Stone Cold for the pinfall! Mr. McMahon did indeed get the last laugh! As confetti poured down from the ceiling, Mr. McMahon and Chris Jericho celebrated -- Chris Jericho is the first-ever Undisputed World Champion!Winner and First Undisputed Champion: Chris Jericho

reviewText: As far as wrestling goes, this DVD is worth it for the last four matches. It's good to own if you're a nut for wrestling history, otherwise, look elsewhere. The women's wrestling match, and the tag team title match are throwaways, and the Hardys' match was a letdown. However, RVD manages to carry the Undertaker.The main event is interesting, even if overbooked.

reviewText: The Christian/Test-Scotty 2 Hotty/Albert tag team match was an average opener. The Intercontinental title match between Edge & William Regal was solid. The Matt Hardy-Jeff Hardy match was so-so and pointless. The World Tag Team title match between The Dudley Boyz against the team of The Big Show & Kane was HORRIBLE. The Hardcore title match between Rob Van Dam & The Undertaker was not bad & a good reminder of RVD's days in ECW. The Women's title match between Trish Stratus & Jacqueline was short and not good. The WWF title match between Steve Austin & Kurt Angle was not great but pretty good. The Worlds title match between Chris Jericho & The Rock was good despite Vince's interference. The title for title match was so-so at best. I give this PPV a 5 out of 10.

reviewText: A lot of people put this ppv down because of the unexpected ending but I thaught it was a very good show. Listed below are my reviews of the matches.Albert & Scotty 2 Hotty vs. Christian & Test(Not a classic but a very solid opener)Edge vs. William Regal(A decent match with a good ending)Jaqueline vs. Trish(A great effort by both divas)Dudley Boyz vs. Big Show & Kane(The worst match on the card. The Big Show & Kane have no chemistry at all)RVD vs. Undertaker(The best hardcore match I have ever seen!. Taker is as sadistic as ever and RVD is in fine form)Kurt Angle vs. Stone Cold Steve Austin(These two men have had many battles but this one stood out from the rest. A fantastic display by both competitors)Chris Jericho vs. The Rock(Another great match from the Jericho/Rock series. Shame about the ending though)Undisputed Title MatchChris Jericho vs. Stone Cold Steve Austin(A superb main event with both men being pushed to their absolute limits. Booker T interfears at the end and helps Jericho get the win)Verdict - There is not many bad points to this ppv. The Undertaker/rvd match along with the Angle/Austin match are worth buying this dvd for alone!.
summary: A great ppv to cap off a great year of wrestling!

reviewText: I saw this on PPV, lets hope the WWF cleans this up a little before releasing it.  The matches were umm well sloppy as he&%.  The intro however is probably the best I've ever seen with Classy Freddy Blassie and a run down of the last 20 years of WWF Champions.  As usual Raw or Smackdown viewers would expect Vince comes out at the beginning of the show (this was the single thing WCW didn't do on Nitro that I actual liked) and goes on his usual tiraid, what a suprise he's interupted by Flair and by the time there done you wonder "what was the point of all that?".  Finally the first match begins and after Test/Christian and Scotty 2 Hotty/Blbert...Hip Hop Hippo..yeah..OK, come out you wish Flair and Vince never left.  The match would generously be considered [garbage] with with Scotty and Albert getting the win.  Edge vs Reagal is better than it sounds but not by much.  Then theres the possible show stealing Hardy vs Hardy match with a prematch interview where you can tell Lita had chin surgery.  The match which seemed like it couldn't miss bombed completely and was very sloppy. Met with absolute silence from the crowd the match mercifully ended with a Jeff win.  The tag straps were up next in a pretty solid match seeing the Dudley's getting the Duke on Kane and the Show.  As usual Rob Van Dam carries the PPV's best match which didn't really spend to much time in the ring by the way.  Regardless Taker and RVD go full tilt and renewed Taker as well a bad mother[...].  A clip is shown of Trish and Rock flirting, like everybody doesn't know Johnson's married.  The Trish vs Jackie match was absolutly horrible with Jackie obviously the more accomplished wrestler.  We finally get to the three whatevers and Austin and Angle which was just like all there other matches with Austin comming out on top and the crowd as fickle as ever.  The Rock and Jericho match was well exactly the same as well with Jericho getting the win with a screw job.  Austin comes out as soon as Rock is pinned and the match isn't all that bad but ultimately another screw job and Jericho is the man, he balls and the crowd boo's but common its about time the monotony is ended.  All in all pretty weak...RVD Taker great match. And Triple H promo AWESOME...M'KA!

reviewText: Simple, one of the best PPV's, it all started with another superb video package like only the WWF can deliver, then Mr. McMahon being interrupted the way he was, was a great way to kick it off.  All matches were good (maybe, well not maybe, the hardy vrs. hardy match could had been way better), and the Undertaker vrs. RVD match was incredible, the UT really proved he can still work with a young new Superstar like RVD, and he did sell for RVD, this match alone was worth my money for this PPV. Did you hear The King say in the Trish/Jackie match "let the puppies out to play" (man, he really likes Trish, and who can blame him). Flair is awesome. The undisputed champion matches (the three of them)were 5 star matches, They can never go wrong with an Angle/Austin match, and the Rock/Jericho match was a great as well, then Austin/Jericho at the final match was good booking, they worked the match simply great, and allthough you knew Jericho wouldn't get the clean victory, I thought it was the right call, and maybe, Jericho needed to win with a little help to make it feel special.A really good, great PPV.
summary: One great company, One great champion...

reviewText: Vengeance was a great way to end an eventful year for the WWE.There were some very surprisingly good matches at Vengeance.1.Scotty 2 Hotty and Albert vs.Test and Christian(Tag Team Match)This match really surprised me. It was a very solid opener with everybody's finisher used at least once.7 out of 10.2.Edge vs.William Regal(WWE Intercontinental Championship Match)This match isn't as bad as everybody says it is.It is slow at spots but it is a match that will satisfy you until the bigger matches come. Edge even speared the steel steps.7 out of 10.3.Jeff Hardy vs.Matt Hardy(Special Referee:Lita)I was expecting a more fast paced match with more high-risk moves than it had, but it still is a good match.7 out of 10.4.Dudley Boyz vs.Kane and Big Show(WWE Tag Team Championship)This isn't what one would call a tag team classic, but it is funny and it was more of a free-for-all.7 out of 10.5.Rob Van Dam vs.The Undertaker(WWE Hardcore Championship)This is definitely one of the best matches on the card. It was a very brutal match with high-flying moves from Van Dam. The way it ended was crazy too.10 out of 10.6.Trish Stratus vs.Jacqueline(WWE Womens Championship)This wasn't a very good match, but then again, not many women's matches are.4 out of 10.7.Stone Cold Steve Austin vs. Kurt Angle(WWE Championship)This was the first match of the tournament to decide the Undisputed Champion, and it didn't disappoint. Though not as good as The Rock and Jericho match, it was still a great match.8 out of 10.8.The Rock vs.Chris Jericho(World Championship)The winner of this match would be meeting Stone Cold after this match since he defeated Kurt Angle.This match was excellent. It was a very physical match and it even had a DDT through the Announcer's Table.10 out of 10.9.Stone Cold Steve Austin vs.Chris Jericho(The Winner Becomes The Undisputed Champion)This match started off immediately after the last match, and before the bell rang, Kurt Angle hit Austin with a chair while The Rock hit a Rock Bottom on Jericho.When the match started officially, a great match came.There was a lot of interference at the end, but this is still a good match.8 out of 10.Vengeance is a great event and highly recommended.

reviewText: The "Vengeance" PPVs have become a personal favorite of mine, and it all started here.  This first one, the 2001 edition, could've been a lot better, but it's still a solid PPV.Scotty & Albert vs. Test & Christian---This match was as pointless as much as it was average.  However, fresh matches like this are meant to be simple fun, and the crowd had a good time with it.  I kind of enjoyed it, too."6.0 out of 10"Intercontinental ChampionshipEdge (champion) vs. William Regal---When one wants to know how the match ends instead of how it plays out...something is terribly wrong!  These two can do better than this, and don't really captivate the audience.  Maybe I need to watch it again, but I'm not looking forward to it."4.0 out of 10"Lita as Special RefereeJeff Hardy vs. Matt Hardy---What a peculiar match!  The most popular Tag Team of 2001 was going to grapple up against each other.  Sadly, I didn't think was very good.  I think that Matt and Jeff relied too much on the hype and psychology instead of the actual wrestling.  Matt is a solid wrestler, but Jeff isn't suited for singles competition.  The crowd got so confused and disinterested that they cheered for Lita instead!  Let's face it - The Hardy Boyz are much better as a team.  It's a good effort by the two brothers, but rather disappointing."5.5 out of 10"Tag Team ChampionshipsThe Dudley Boyz (champions) vs. Big Show & Kane---This isn't a very good tag team contest at all.  It's kind of sloppy and uncoordinated.  However, just like the opening Tag Team Match, sometimes these frenetic and disorganized matches have a way of keeping our attention.  The Dudleyz and the challengers put on a match that is not well-executed, but never boring.  I don't know - watch at your own risk."5.5 out of 10"Hardcore ChampionshipThe Undertaker vs. Rob Van Dam (champion)---This one had such high expectations, that maybe it couldn't meet them.  Despite not being very Hardcore, it was still a crazy and good showing.  The biggest problem isn't even Taker or RVD; it was the camerawork and audio.  I'm sure the moves and risks that Taker and RVD performed were painful, but we couldn't always see or hear what was going on.  It kind of takes you out of the experience.  However, a great finale and some wild action still make this a good one!  I wish RVD and Taker had more matches - they really work well together."7.0 out of 10"Women's ChampionshipTrish Stratus (champion) vs. Jacqueline---Since the Women's title came back at "Survivor Series 2001", could the division hold up?  Well, not by the looks of this one.  Moves are flubbed, and we don't get a real sense of this being a title match.  The crowd was active, but chanted more for the "puppies" than the actual contest.  Once again, a good effort by both women, but mediocre execution."5.0 out of 10"WWF ChampionshipKurt Angle vs. Stone Cold (champion)---Angle faced Steve Austin for 3 months in a row, and then betrayed him at "Survivor Series 2001".  These two had a lot to live up to, and they delivered.  Sure, you'll some similar spots and offense from their other matches, but Angle and Austin always made it work.  A very good match!"7.5 out of 10"World ChampionshipThe Rock (champion) vs. Chris Jericho---Now, this was the match of the night!  I love the "No Mercy 2001" & "Royal Rumble 2002" matches between these two, but this is a perfect companion to those bouts.  Unlike the Austin/Angle matches, each one of the Y2J/Rock contests feel different.  Jericho has a marvelous gift - he keeps talking and vents his attiude 'while' wrestling.  The Rock is a little more off balanced, but he's good here too.  I didn't think Jericho was championship-material until he and The Rock grappled up -- how wrong I was!  What hurts this one is that outside interference determined the winner here.  "The Undisputed Champion" shouldn't be crowned as a result of cheating.  Make no mistake - this is still one of the best matches of 2001!"8.5 out of 10"Undisputed WWF ChampionshipChris Jericho vs. Stone Cold---Well, Stone Cold gave a much better performance in this main event match than against Angle.  This one didn't match up to The Rock/Jericho match, but is was very good.  Jericho especially earned his pay tonight!  A strong back-and-forth faceoff with plenty of close finishes.  My only gripe is that there's too much outisde interference.  I love when the WWF/WWE makes big unexpected surprises, but there were so many run-ins that it was exhausting.  Chris Jericho could've solidifed his status as a WWF/WWE Superstar on his own, but the WWF instead opted for the screwjob approach.  But when all is said and done, Chris Jericho is the only Undisputed Champion to date -- and he deserved it too!"7.5 out of 10""Vengeance 2001" was a decent closing PPV to the year.  2001 was one long ride, and this event gave a nice close with some good matches.  Because there are NO FEATURES, this is hard to recommend with its up-and-down card.  Why did WWF opt for this?  If you're into wrestling itself, then this is a solid addition.  But if WWF/WWE "DVD" is the reason you collect, you might want to pass it up.  Still, check out other reviews and see how it adds up.  For me, the "Vengeance" lineage began here, and seeing the Undisputed tournament is worth the price.

reviewText: Vengeance 2001The WWE and WCW titles would finally be unified (they shouldn't have waited so long to do it though) and there was massive hype. But did the show live up to expectations?Scotty 2 Hotty & Albert V Test and ChristianThis match was only announced on Heat. Suprisingly though, the crowd got into it and the match was good, especially towards the end when it got pretty exciting. 7/10Interconternential title - Edge V William RegalThis was a clash of styles, but the match was actually pretty good and enjoyable. Edge spears the steps accidently. 7/10Jeff Hardy V Matt HardyFirst of all - no one wanted this to happen: the tag team division was already suffering, so why they want to break up one of the best tag teams around? Anyway, we all hoped for a brilliant high-flying ariel match, but what we got was a crap mat-wrestling match. The Hardys actually din't appear again for about 2 months because of this match. Very disappointing. 3/10Tag titles - Dudleys  V Big Show and KaneThis was quite an amusing match, with a funny part involving Stacey. Kane and Show have a misunderstanding allowing the Dudleys to retain. 6/10Hardcore title - Rob Van Dam V UndertakerThis was the match of the night. It was a brilliant hardcore match. They fight through the crowd and into a storage area. Then they fight on the stage and it eventually ends when Taker chokeslamms RVD right off the stage through a table! 9/10Women's title Trish Stratus V JacquelineWhy the hell do WWE always put the women so high on the card? A crap match, as usual. 3/10WWE title - Stone Cold Steve Austin  V Kurt AngleThey put on a good match here. Angle and Austin are both great wrestlers, and the ending is clean and good. 2nd best match of the night. 8/10World (former WCW) title - The Rock V Chris JerichoThis was a little slow, but an enjoyable match with the crowd really into it. They use an announce table at one point. It's quite suprising to see Jericho win. 8/10Unification match Undisputed title - Stone Cold V Chris JerichoThere was so much on the line, and the match was a bit to short. It was kind of unfair that Jericho got no rest at all. I was very suprised when I first watched this (the day after it happend) to see Chris Jericho win to become the first ever UNDISPUTED champion. 8/10OverallThis wasn't a bad PPV as it had some good matches (Taker/RVD and Austin/Angle were the best). However it was way overhyped and couldn't live up to it.
summary: A historic PPV, but way too overhyped

reviewText: Vengeance crowned the first ever undisputed champion and this was just a good ending to a sensational year in ppv's. This was also Jerry Lawler's first commentated ppv in 2001 since No Way Out, so it was good to hear him back in action with JR.It starts out with Mr. McMahon coming out to the ring to address the fans about the situation that happened the past Thursday on Smackdown with the whole Kiss my A55 thing. Ric Flair would come out to shut up McMahon and then the ppv would start.1. Scotty 2 Hotty & Albert vs. Christian & TestThe match started with a little brawl on the outside which led to the match in the ring. There were some very good brawling and impact moves. All four men look good in this one. There was some funny spots with S2H & Albert. I thought it had a pretty good ending. Pretty solid opening contest. 3.5/52. Intercontinental ChampionshipEdge vs. William RegalBefore the match started, Regal did a pretty good heel interview with the Coach. The match was pretty good with some nice counters with some good back and fourth action. Edge would go for the spear on the outside but would miss Regal and run right into the ring steps. Regal would find some brass knucks but doesn't get a chance to use them. Edge hit the spear out of thin air which was made the ending better to me. 3.5/53.  Matt Hardy vs. Jeff Hardy with Lita as the special RefereePretty solid match up right here, and surprisingly the Hardys work pretty well against each other. Matt would try to work on Jeff's leg about mid way in the match so Jeff wouldn't be able to pull off any of his high flying Hardy offense. There were some pretty good counters and high risk. Some good wrestling moves applied as well. It had a pretty questionable ending but it worked in well. Good match. 4/54. WWE Tag Team ChampionshipThe Dudley Boyz w/ Stacy Keibler vs. Big Show and KaneI believe Show and Kane always made a good big man team. I believe they work well as a team and they make a good big team duo. There was some nice double team moves and a little high risk. A good funny spot with Show & Stacy mid way in the match. Some good hard shots too. A few nice counters as well. There was some miss cues on the part of Kane & Show which costed them the match. Pretty good tag match, I really enjoyed this one. 3.5/55. Hardcore ChampionshipUndertaker vs. RVDIt seemed in the early going that Undertaker was just over powering the smaller RVD. It had some pretty fast paced action. It soon would fall out into the crowd and get more hardcore out there. Some nice high aerial offense from Van Dam out there. Some nice weapon use. It had a pretty solid and hardcore ending. Good title match up. 4/56. Women's ChampionshipTrish Stratus vs. JacquelineThis was a pretty decent back and fourth women's match up. There were some nice physcial spots with some good wrestling moves and counters. Nice wrestled up women's contest right here. A little short but it served its purpose to set up the Undisputed title matches. 3/57. WWE ChampionshipKurt Angle vs. Stone Cold Steve AustinThis match was very different from their previous ecounters but it was great though. It had some good wrestling and some good brawling. Austin really trys to ware down Angle in the beginning. Austin really works on Angles arm in this one. They really brawled each other out on the outside where Angle applied the figure four on Austin on the ring post. Some good reversals and good counters, just a great solid match up. 5/58. World Heavyweight ChampionshipThe Rock vs. Chris JerichoThis was a pretty solid title match up as well. And this match to was different from their previous encounter from No Mercy. The match was more fast paced and more physical. Some nice wrestling moves used too by both men. It seemed to drag on a little bit but not that much. It had some good counters and I believed that this match was more personal then the Angle/Austin Match before. There were some few high risk and a good table spot as well. I wasn't really all too fond of the ending but it was good. Another good one right here. 4.5/59. Undisputed ChampionshipStone Cold Steve Austin vs. Chris JerichoBefore the match got under way, Angle would come out and hit Austin with a chair and the Rock would Rock Bottom Jericho. The match would then start and these two had a pretty good match up as well. They put on a good showing on the outside just beating on each other out there. Jericho took some hard slams on the hard exposed concrete floor. They put on some good brawling and some nice counters. Flair and McMahon would interfer which would set up their match at the Royal Rumble. It had a pretty cheap ending but it all fitted in. A nice solid undisputed match up. 4.5/5Vengeance topped off and unbelieveable year of 2001. This is a great ppv to check out if yall haven't already. Pretty solid card.
summary: A great end to a great year in ppv's

reviewText: Vengeance 2001 marked the beginning of the Undisputed champion era. Many guys like; The Undertaker, Hulk Hogan, Triple H, The Rock, and Brock Lesnar won the title at different times in 2002. But the one man who won the title in the very beginning, held that title the longest of them all. That man is Chris Jericho and the event he won it at was Vengeance.Test and Christian vs. Scotty 2 Hotty and Albert:These were two makeshift teams at the end of 2001, but they weren't as bad as the teams that were made at the end of 2004. A okay opener.Short match and it was weird seeing Albert and Scotty as a legit tag team but the action certainly wasn't bad. Funny moment when Christian went for the worm, but Albert nailed his "Baldobomb" to pin Christian. 7/10Intercontinental MatchEdge [Champion] vs William Regal:This is one of those types of rivalries that go on for months, but unfortunately this was one of those bad rivalries. Kinda like Cena and Kenzo Suzuki.The match itself was good, but really slow in some spots thanks to Regal. It was a little too old school from him than I could take. Good moment when Edge tried to spear Regal off the ring but hit the steps! Regal tried to use the brass knucks but Edge speared him to win. 7.5/10Jeff vs. Matt Hardy:Poor Hardy Boyz, we will probably never see them again in the WWE. I hope that doesn't happen, but until the day comes when they return, watch old tapes with matches like this and others in them.Lita was the special guest referee in the match. Lots of high flying moves obviously, just look at who's in the ring. A lot ot Twist of Fates in this match, including one that Matt tried to do from the top rope, but Jeff hit his Swanton Bomb to win. 8/10 [Fair length match]Tag Team Championship MatchDudley Boyz [Champions] vs. Big Show and Kane:Both Kane and Big Show tore apart the Dudleys everytime they tagged each other in the ring. Another funny moment when Big Show actually pulled down Stacy Keibler's skirt! That sure got Jerry Lawler going!The Dudley Boyz win after Big Show's head hits the turnbuckle after he accidently hit Kane and then got the 3D. 8/10 Good match.Hardcore ChampionshipRob Van Dam [Champion] vs. The UndertakerI liked this match a lot, two very different styles meeting in a no holds barred enviroment. The match went all over the place, from the crowd to the backstage area. Taker used some chairs and RVD used a trash can at one point.Another cool part was when RVD hit the rolling thunder on Taker on the stage area! The ending was barbaric with RVD getting chokeslammed through 3 tables off the stage! The Undertaker winsto become the new champ. 9/10 Nice matchWomen's ChampionshipTrish [Champion] vs. JacquelineThis was good for a women's championship. I never saw Jacqueline in a real type match for the Women's title, so it was new watching her fight Trish. The match was very short and Trish wins. After the match the two women shake hands. 7/10World Heavyweight ChampionshipStone Cold Steve Austin [Champion] vs. Kurt Angle:Amazing match, both men worked well together. With Stone Cold using his brawling type moves against Angle's wrestling moves. One move that was great was when Angle gave the Figure Four to Austin while Austin's legs were wrapped around the ring post.Austin even used a lot of German Suplexes on Angle himself. The Rattlesnake won after giving the Stunner to Angle. 9/10 Good MatchWCW Championship Match:The Rock [Champion] vs. Chris JerichoThis was a good match. A lot better than their matches at the Royal Rumble 2002 and No Mercy of that year. The Rock even gave the DDT to Jericho through an announce table!Vince McMahon came out and distracted the ref. Then the Rock beat up McMahon, but Jericho hit a low blow and the Lionsault to become the WCW World Champion. 9/10 Good MatchUndisputed Championship MatchSteve Austin [WWF Champion] vs. Chris Jericho [WCW Champion]It was chaos right after Jericho pinned the Rock cause Austin came down to the ring, but then Angle came from behind with a chair and wasted The Rattlesnake. Then the Rock laid the Smackdown on Jericho with the Rock Bottom, then chased after Angle.Jericho hung out despite the fact that he literally had no time to rest. He even was backdropped off a table right onto the concrete. Vince McMahon and Ric Flair then come down the ring and Flair gets knocked out and then McMahon gets knocked out by Austin.The ending was a screwjob, Booker T comes down and nails Austin. Chris Jericho wins and becomes the first ever Undisputed Champion. 10/10 Great match, no matter who you were rooting for.Vengeance 2001 was a great ppv. Despite the opening match and the Women's match and the Intercontinental match the other 6 matches are well worth it. This was a great way to end 2001.
summary: The day the Chris Jericho era began.......
